Dialogue: 0,0:02:10.82,0:02:18.04,辉注,,0,0,0,,美国使用的NTSC制使用525行扫描线
Dialogue: 1,0:00:01.73,0:00:07.25,辉中,,0,0,0,,1969年7月20日，阿波罗11号在月球着陆
Dialogue: 2,0:00:01.73,0:00:07.25,辉英,,0,0,0,,On the 20th of July, 1969, Apollo 11 landed on the Moon.
Dialogue: 1,0:00:07.64,0:00:15.70,辉中,,0,0,0,,全世界大约有6亿人观看了尼尔·阿姆斯特朗在月球踩下第一个脚印的直播
Dialogue: 2,0:00:07.64,0:00:15.70,辉英,,0,0,0,,600 million people around the world watched as Neil Armstrong took mankind's first steps onto the Lunar surface.
Dialogue: 1,0:00:16.37,0:00:19.10,辉中,,0,0,0,,那一刻记录了一代人兴奋的回忆
Dialogue: 2,0:00:16.37,0:00:19.10,辉英,,0,0,0,,This moment captured the excitement of a generation
Dialogue: 1,0:00:19.10,0:00:24.85,辉中,,0,0,0,,也让肯尼迪总统在60年代末登月的承诺得以兑现
Dialogue: 2,0:00:19.10,0:00:24.85,辉英,,0,0,0,,and fulfilled President Kennedy's goal of landing a man on the Moon by the end of the decade.
Dialogue: 1,0:00:25.45,0:00:32.00,辉中,,0,0,0,,可NASA是如何让月球上的画面一路传回地球让无数人看到的？
Dialogue: 2,0:00:25.45,0:00:32.00,辉英,,0,0,0,,But how did NASA broadcast live footage from the Moon all the way to a record amount of people back on Earth?
Dialogue: 1,0:00:32.86,0:00:39.16,辉中,,0,0,0,,本期视频，我们将了解视频直播画面从月球传回时会遇到的挑战
Dialogue: 2,0:00:32.86,0:00:39.16,辉英,,0,0,0,,In this video, we're going to look at the the challenges involved in broadcasting live footage from the Moon.
Dialogue: 1,0:00:39.52,0:00:42.93,辉中,,0,0,0,,并了解克服这些挑战所用到的技术
Dialogue: 2,0:00:39.52,0:00:42.93,辉英,,0,0,0,,We're also going to look at the technology that went into making it happen
Dialogue: 1,0:00:43.15,0:00:46.56,辉中,,0,0,0,,以及这些技术在之后的阿波罗任务中有何改进
Dialogue: 2,0:00:43.15,0:00:46.56,辉英,,0,0,0,,and how it was developed for future Apollo missions.
Dialogue: 1,0:00:47.94,0:00:54.92,辉中,,0,0,0,,在60年代早期，NASA开始着手研发送人类登月的火箭和飞船
Dialogue: 2,0:00:47.94,0:00:54.92,辉英,,0,0,0,,In the early 60's, NASA began working on the rocket and spacecraft that would eventually take humans to the Moon.
Dialogue: 1,0:00:55.77,0:01:00.12,辉中,,0,0,0,,可当时美国送进太空的宇航员屈指可数
Dialogue: 2,0:00:55.77,0:01:00.12,辉英,,0,0,0,,At the time, America had only sent a handful of astronauts into space,
Dialogue: 1,0:01:00.16,0:01:03.06,辉中,,0,0,0,,更没有人离开过近地轨道
Dialogue: 2,0:01:00.16,0:01:03.06,辉英,,0,0,0,,and no human had ever left Earth's orbit.
Dialogue: 1,0:01:04.12,0:01:08.72,辉中,,0,0,0,,送人类登月这个充满野心的计划遭到了无数质疑
Dialogue: 2,0:01:04.12,0:01:08.72,辉英,,0,0,0,,This ambitious plan to send humans to the Moon was met with a lot of skepticism
Dialogue: 1,0:01:09.10,0:01:16.12,辉中,,0,0,0,,所以NASA也明白宇航员在月球行走的直播将是登月任务最有力的证明
Dialogue: 2,0:01:09.10,0:01:16.12,辉英,,0,0,0,,and NASA knew that live video of the astronauts walking on the Moon would be crucial for the mission's credibility.
Dialogue: 1,0:01:16.57,0:01:23.44,辉中,,0,0,0,,NASA与美国西屋公司签约，要求后者设计制造一款小型黑白相机
Dialogue: 2,0:01:16.57,0:01:23.44,辉英,,0,0,0,,NASA contracted electronics company "Westinghouse" to design and manufacture a small black and white camera 
Dialogue: 1,0:01:23.56,0:01:27.38,辉中,,0,0,0,,从而拍摄人类首次登月的镜头
Dialogue: 2,0:01:23.56,0:01:27.38,辉英,,0,0,0,,that would be capable of capturing man's first step on the Moon.
Dialogue: 1,0:01:28.30,0:01:32.16,辉中,,0,0,0,,相机需能在仅7瓦的功耗下运转
Dialogue: 2,0:01:28.30,0:01:32.16,辉英,,0,0,0,,This camera would need to operate on a mere 7 Watt power source
Dialogue: 1,0:01:32.37,0:01:38.30,辉中,,0,0,0,,并能承受月球表面的强烈辐射与巨大温差
Dialogue: 2,0:01:32.37,0:01:38.30,辉英,,0,0,0,,and be able to survive the harsh radiation and extreme temperatures found on the Moon's surface.
Dialogue: 1,0:01:39.13,0:01:44.32,辉中,,0,0,0,,最重要的是，登月舱还需要将视频直播画面
Dialogue: 2,0:01:39.13,0:01:44.32,辉英,,0,0,0,,Most importantly, the Lunar Module would need to be able to send the live video feed
Dialogue: 1,0:01:44.32,0:01:50.38,辉中,,0,0,0,,和其他无线电、遥测数据一起传回地球
Dialogue: 2,0:01:44.32,0:01:50.38,辉英,,0,0,0,,all the way back to Earth, along with the other radio and telemetry data that was already being sent back.
Dialogue: 1,0:01:51.56,0:01:56.23,辉中,,0,0,0,,NASA意识到阿波罗任务需要一款全新的通信系统
Dialogue: 2,0:01:51.56,0:01:56.23,辉英,,0,0,0,,NASA realized that the Apollo missions would require a brand new communications system
Dialogue: 1,0:01:56.23,0:01:58.98,辉中,,0,0,0,,才能把数据从月球传回地球
Dialogue: 2,0:01:56.23,0:01:58.98,辉英,,0,0,0,,in order to send data back from the Moon.
Dialogue: 1,0:01:59.46,0:02:02.09,辉中,,0,0,0,,于是他们研发了一款叫“统一S波段”的系统
Dialogue: 2,0:01:59.46,0:02:02.09,辉英,,0,0,0,,They developed a system called "Unified S-band"
Dialogue: 1,0:02:02.09,0:02:07.74,辉中,,0,0,0,,可以将各自不同频率的遥测信号、指令、声音、视频信号
Dialogue: 2,0:02:02.09,0:02:07.74,辉英,,0,0,0,,which could send: telemetry, command, voice and television data using different frequencies
Dialogue: 1,0:02:07.74,0:02:10.46,辉中,,0,0,0,,结合为单一天线发送
Dialogue: 2,0:02:07.74,0:02:10.46,辉英,,0,0,0,,but combined into a single antenna.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:10.82,0:02:18.04,辉中,,0,0,0,,然而即使有了新系统，信号带宽也不够传输525行的标清电视信号
Dialogue: 2,0:02:10.82,0:02:18.04,辉英,,0,0,0,,However, even with this new system, there wasn't enough bandwidth available for a standard 525 line video camera.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:18.96,0:02:21.88,辉中,,0,0,0,,为了让视频流能“挤进”带宽中
Dialogue: 2,0:02:18.96,0:02:21.88,辉英,,0,0,0,,In order for the video feed to fit into the downlink,
Dialogue: 1,0:02:22.02,0:02:24.60,辉中,,0,0,0,,西屋公司研发了低扫描频率相机
Dialogue: 2,0:02:22.02,0:02:24.60,辉英,,0,0,0,,Westinghouse developed a slow-scan camera
Dialogue: 1,0:02:24.69,0:02:30.08,辉中,,0,0,0,,只传输325行扫描线、每秒仅10帧的画面
Dialogue: 2,0:02:24.69,0:02:30.08,辉英,,0,0,0,,which transmitted just 325 scan lines at a mere 10 frames per second.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:30.74,0:02:35.04,辉中,,0,0,0,,相机会通过线缆连接至登月舱
Dialogue: 2,0:02:30.74,0:02:35.04,辉英,,0,0,0,,This camera would be connected to the Lunar Module via an electrical cable,
Dialogue: 1,0:02:35.18,0:02:37.74,辉中,,0,0,0,,从而可以在着陆点附近移动
Dialogue: 2,0:02:35.18,0:02:37.74,辉英,,0,0,0,,allowing it to be moved around the landing site.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:38.58,0:02:41.64,辉中,,0,0,0,,视频信号会经由登月舱天线
Dialogue: 2,0:02:38.58,0:02:41.64,辉英,,0,0,0,,The video signal would be transmitted from the Lunar Module's antenna
Dialogue: 1,0:02:41.77,0:02:44.14,辉中,,0,0,0,,传回澳大利亚的追踪站
Dialogue: 2,0:02:41.77,0:02:44.14,辉英,,0,0,0,,back to a tracking station in Australia
Dialogue: 1,0:02:44.32,0:02:47.69,辉中,,0,0,0,,在澳大利亚，NASA将画面转换成标准广播电视信号
Dialogue: 2,0:02:44.32,0:02:47.69,辉英,,0,0,0,,where NASA would convert the image into a standard broadcast signal.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:48.54,0:02:52.09,辉中,,0,0,0,,再将信号利用通信卫星转发给休斯敦的控制中心
Dialogue: 2,0:02:48.54,0:02:52.09,辉英,,0,0,0,,That signal would then be transmitted up to a communications satellite
Dialogue: 1,0:02:52.09,0:02:54.53,辉中,,0,0,0,,再将信号利用通信卫星转发给休斯敦的控制中心
Dialogue: 2,0:02:52.09,0:02:54.53,辉英,,0,0,0,,and back down to mission control in Houston
Dialogue: 1,0:02:54.53,0:02:57.33,辉中,,0,0,0,,休斯敦再将信号转发给世界其他地方
Dialogue: 2,0:02:54.53,0:02:57.33,辉英,,0,0,0,,where they would broadcast it to the rest of the world.
Dialogue: 1,0:02:58.05,0:03:02.61,辉中,,0,0,0,,然而，在月球开直播的挑战还没完
Dialogue: 2,0:02:58.05,0:03:02.61,辉英,,0,0,0,,However, the challenges of filming on the Moon didn't stop there.
Dialogue: 1,0:03:04.09,0:03:08.54,辉中,,0,0,0,,月球表面和黑暗的太空背景产生的超高对比度
Dialogue: 2,0:03:04.09,0:03:08.54,辉英,,0,0,0,,The incredibly high contrast between the Lunar surface and the darkness of space
Dialogue: 1,0:03:08.76,0:03:12.80,辉中,,0,0,0,,会导致在月球上捕获清晰图像异常困难
Dialogue: 2,0:03:08.76,0:03:12.80,辉英,,0,0,0,,would make capturing a clear image on the Moon extremely difficult.
Dialogue: 1,0:03:13.74,0:03:18.45,辉中,,0,0,0,,为解决这个问题，西屋公司使用了其曾为国防部研发的绝密技术
Dialogue: 2,0:03:13.74,0:03:18.45,辉英,,0,0,0,,To solve this problem, Westinghouse used a piece of classified technology
Dialogue: 1,0:03:18.45,0:03:21.12,辉中,,0,0,0,,为解决这个问题，西屋公司使用了其曾为国防部研发的绝密技术
Dialogue: 2,0:03:18.45,0:03:21.12,辉英,,0,0,0,,which they had developed for the Department of Defense.
Dialogue: 1,0:03:21.84,0:03:25.10,辉中,,0,0,0,,他们研发了一款特制的低亮度成像管
Dialogue: 2,0:03:21.84,0:03:25.10,辉英,,0,0,0,,They had developed a special low-light imaging tube
Dialogue: 1,0:03:25.16,0:03:29.00,辉中,,0,0,0,,其曾在越南战争中用于丛林侦查相机上
Dialogue: 2,0:03:25.16,0:03:29.00,辉英,,0,0,0,,which was used on jungle surveillance cameras during the Vietnam War.
Dialogue: 1,0:03:29.88,0:03:35.48,辉中,,0,0,0,,它能在低亮度下捕获移动物体，且不会让画面完全模糊
Dialogue: 2,0:03:29.88,0:03:35.48,辉英,,0,0,0,,This could capture moving objects at low light levels without completely blurring the image.
Dialogue: 1,0:03:36.61,0:03:42.14,辉中,,0,0,0,,随着人类首次登月任务的逐渐接近，相机也准备好了
Dialogue: 2,0:03:36.61,0:03:42.14,辉英,,0,0,0,,As the first manned Apollo missions loomed ever closer, the camera was ready
Dialogue: 1,0:03:42.29,0:03:47.53,辉中,,0,0,0,,它将在阿波罗9号上进行其首次、也是唯一的一次测试
Dialogue: 2,0:03:42.29,0:03:47.53,辉英,,0,0,0,,and it was on Apollo 9 where it would go through it's first and only test.
Dialogue: 1,0:03:48.46,0:03:50.77,辉中,,0,0,0,,相机放在了登月舱上
Dialogue: 2,0:03:48.46,0:03:50.77,辉英,,0,0,0,,The camera was placed on the Lunar Module
Dialogue: 1,0:03:50.84,0:03:55.60,辉中,,0,0,0,,在任务中相机和其他通信系统的测试非常成功
Dialogue: 2,0:03:50.84,0:03:55.60,辉英,,0,0,0,,and the mission successfully tested the camera along with the communication system.
Dialogue: 1,0:03:56.60,0:04:01.06,辉中,,0,0,0,,相机的下一个任务就是将人类第一次登月的画面直播出去
Dialogue: 2,0:03:56.60,0:04:01.06,辉英,,0,0,0,,The camera's next task would be capturing man's first step onto the Moon.
Dialogue: 1,0:04:03.32,0:04:09.69,辉中,,0,0,0,,1969年7月20日，阿波罗11号在月球着陆
Dialogue: 2,0:04:03.32,0:04:09.69,辉英,,0,0,0,,20th of July 1969, Apollo 11 touched down on the Moon.
Dialogue: 1,0:04:10.62,0:04:14.78,辉中,,0,0,0,,置于登月舱侧面的相机对准了登月舱的梯子
Dialogue: 2,0:04:10.62,0:04:14.78,辉英,,0,0,0,,With the camera placed on the side of the Lunar Module aiming towards the ladders,
Dialogue: 1,0:04:15.02,0:04:19.92,辉中,,0,0,0,,巴兹·奥尔德林拨动舱内的断路器，开启了相机
Dialogue: 2,0:04:15.02,0:04:19.92,辉英,,0,0,0,,Buzz Aldrin hit a circuit breaker from inside the cabin to turn on the camera.
Dialogue: 1,0:04:21.00,0:04:24.58,辉中,,0,0,0,,直播一开始，画面是上下颠倒的
Dialogue: 2,0:04:21.00,0:04:24.58,辉英,,0,0,0,,At the start of the broadcast, the footage appeared to be upside down.
Dialogue: 1,0:04:24.89,0:04:30.17,辉中,,0,0,0,,澳大利亚负责信号的技术人员很快将画面翻转回来
Dialogue: 2,0:04:24.89,0:04:30.17,辉英,,0,0,0,,Video operators in Australia who were handling the signal quickly inverted the image to fix this issue,
Dialogue: 1,0:04:30.38,0:04:33.33,辉中,,0,0,0,,刚好赶上阿姆斯特朗踏上月球的画面
Dialogue: 2,0:04:30.38,0:04:33.33,辉英,,0,0,0,,just in time for Neil stepping onto the Moon.
Dialogue: 1,0:04:34.53,0:04:36.80,辉中,,0,0,0,,尽管画面的对比度很高
Dialogue: 2,0:04:34.53,0:04:36.80,辉英,,0,0,0,,There was a great deal of contrast in the image
Dialogue: 1,0:04:36.80,0:04:39.76,辉中,,0,0,0,,在转换过程中丢失了很多细节
Dialogue: 2,0:04:36.80,0:04:39.76,辉英,,0,0,0,,and a lot of detail was lost through the conversion process,
Dialogue: 1,0:04:40.10,0:04:44.29,辉中,,0,0,0,,但镜头还是清晰地记录下这最具有历史意义的一刻
Dialogue: 2,0:04:40.10,0:04:44.29,辉英,,0,0,0,,but the footage clearly captured one of the most historic moments in history.
Dialogue: 1,0:04:45.32,0:04:50.98,辉中,,0,0,0,,相机在任务中运行一切顺利，且至今还在月球上
Dialogue: 2,0:04:45.32,0:04:50.98,辉英,,0,0,0,,The camera performed its job perfectly throughout the mission and remains on the Moon to this day.
Dialogue: 1,0:04:52.04,0:04:55.53,辉中,,0,0,0,,在之后的阿波罗任务中，NASA使用了更先进的相机
Dialogue: 2,0:04:52.04,0:04:55.53,辉英,,0,0,0,,Future Apollo missions used a more advanced version of the camera
Dialogue: 1,0:04:55.60,0:04:59.18,辉中,,0,0,0,,可以记录色度信息，且在低亮度下有更好的表现
Dialogue: 2,0:04:55.60,0:04:59.18,辉英,,0,0,0,,which filmed in color and had better low light performance.
Dialogue: 1,0:04:59.82,0:05:05.32,辉中,,0,0,0,,阿波罗15、16、17号的相机还安装在了月球车上
Dialogue: 2,0:04:59.82,0:05:05.32,辉英,,0,0,0,,Apollo 15, 16 and 17 cameras were also placed onto the Lunar rover.
Dialogue: 1,0:05:06.24,0:05:10.02,辉中,,0,0,0,,当宇航员离开月球的时候，他们把月球车停在一定距离外
Dialogue: 2,0:05:06.24,0:05:10.02,辉英,,0,0,0,,Once the Astronauts were leaving the Moon, they parked the rover at a distance
Dialogue: 1,0:05:10.04,0:05:14.52,辉中,,0,0,0,,而任务控制中心的相机操作员会发送指令让相机抬头
Dialogue: 2,0:05:10.04,0:05:14.52,辉英,,0,0,0,,and a camera operator back at mission control would command the camera to tilt up,
Dialogue: 1,0:05:14.77,0:05:18.28,辉中,,0,0,0,,在宇航员从月球起飞时继续跟踪拍摄
Dialogue: 2,0:05:14.77,0:05:18.28,辉英,,0,0,0,,following the astronauts as they left the Moon's surface.
Dialogue: 1,0:05:20.44,0:05:22.77,辉中,,0,0,0,,所以虽然我们还没重返月球
Dialogue: 2,0:05:20.44,0:05:22.77,辉英,,0,0,0,,So although we have never been back to the Moon,
Dialogue: 1,0:05:22.84,0:05:26.80,辉中,,0,0,0,,我们还是要感激那些为了拍下这些历史瞬间的人所付出的努力
Dialogue: 2,0:05:22.84,0:05:26.80,辉英,,0,0,0,,we can appreciate the effort that went into capturing these historical moments
Dialogue: 1,0:05:26.80,0:05:29.57,辉中,,0,0,0,,而那些画面将是人类永远的财富
Dialogue: 2,0:05:26.80,0:05:29.57,辉英,,0,0,0,,in a way that we will cherish forever.
Dialogue: 1,0:05:30.46,0:05:35.65,辉中,,0,0,0,,而当我们未来重返月球时，我们今天拥有的先进摄像技术
Dialogue: 2,0:05:30.46,0:05:35.65,辉英,,0,0,0,,And when we do eventually return to the Moon, the advanced camera technology that we have today
Dialogue: 1,0:05:35.65,0:05:39.94,辉中,,0,0,0,,还将拍摄更加壮丽的瞬间
